
Complete Theory: Array vs ArrayList vs LinkedList in Java
1. ARRAY
int[] arr = new int[5];

Array is the most basic data structure.

It stores elements in contiguous memory locations.

Internal Working

Suppose:

int[] arr = {10,20,30,40};

Memory:

Index:   0    1    2    3
Value:  10   20   30   40

Internally memory looks continuous:

1000 -> 10
1004 -> 20
1008 -> 30
1012 -> 40

Each integer occupies 4 bytes.

Why Array Access is O(1)

Formula:

Address=Base+(index×sizeOfElement)

Example:

To access index 3:

1000+(3×4)=1012

Direct jump happens.

No traversal needed.

That’s why:

arr[3]

is O(1).

Characteristics
Feature	Array
Size	Fixed
Memory	Contiguous
Access	Very Fast
Dynamic Resize	❌
Primitive Support	✅
Thread Safe	❌
Advantages
✅ Extremely fast random access
arr[i]

O(1)

✅ Lowest memory usage

Only actual data stored.

No extra objects/pointers.

✅ CPU cache friendly

Continuous memory improves performance.

✅ Supports primitives directly
int[]
char[]
double[]

No boxing/unboxing.

Disadvantages
❌ Fixed size

Cannot grow dynamically.

❌ Insertion/deletion expensive

Need shifting.

Example:

[10,20,30,40]

Insert 15 at index 1

[10,15,20,30,40]

Everything shifts right.

Time = O(n)

When to Use

✅ DP
✅ Matrix
✅ Frequency count
✅ Performance-critical code

2. ARRAYLIST
ArrayList<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>();
Internal Working

ArrayList internally uses:

Object[] elementData;

Meaning:

internally it is STILL an array.
Default Capacity

Java creates:

capacity = 10

initially (when first element added).

Size vs Capacity
Size

Actual elements count.

list.size()
Capacity

Internal array size.

Example:

Capacity = 10
Size = 3

means:

array can hold 10 elements
only 3 currently present
Resizing Mechanism

When array becomes full:

Java creates bigger array.

Growth formula:

newCapacity = oldCapacity + oldCapacity/2

Approximately:

1.5x growth
Example

Capacity:

10 → 15 → 22 → 33 → 49
Why add() is Amortized O(1)

Most inserts:

list.add(x)

simply append.

O(1)

BUT occasionally:

new array created
all elements copied

That resize step is O(n).

Since resizing happens rarely:
Average = Amortized O(1)

Characteristics
Feature	ArrayList
Internal Structure	Dynamic Array
Random Access	Fast
Dynamic Size	✅
Thread Safe	❌
Allows Duplicates	✅
Maintains Order	✅
Advantages
✅ Dynamic resizing

No fixed size issue.

✅ Fast random access

Internally array-based.

O(1)

✅ Rich API
add()
remove()
contains()
sort()
✅ Better practical performance than LinkedList

Due to cache locality.

Disadvantages
❌ Insert/delete in middle costly

Requires shifting.

O(n)

❌ Boxing overhead
ArrayList<Integer>

stores Integer objects.

Not primitive int.

❌ Resize operation costly occasionally

Copies entire array.

ArrayList Capacity Tuning

You can optimize:

new ArrayList<>(1000);

Avoids multiple resizes.

Very important in performance systems.

LOAD FACTOR?

❌ ArrayList DOES NOT HAVE LOAD FACTOR.

This is HashMap concept.

People often confuse:

capacity growth
with
load factor

Different things.

3. LINKEDLIST
LinkedList<Integer> list = new LinkedList<>();
Internal Structure

Java uses:

Doubly Linked List

Each node:

class Node {
    E item;
    Node next;
    Node prev;
}
Memory Representation
[10 | * ] -> [20 | * ] -> [30 | * ]

Each node stores:

data
next pointer
prev pointer
Characteristics
Feature	LinkedList
Internal Structure	Doubly Linked Nodes
Random Access	Slow
Dynamic Size	✅
Memory Usage	High
Queue Operations	Excellent
Advantages
✅ Fast insertion/deletion

No shifting needed.

Pointer updates only.

✅ Excellent for Queue/Deque
addFirst()
removeFirst()

O(1)

✅ No resizing needed

Nodes allocated dynamically.

Disadvantages
❌ Random access very slow
list.get(1000)

Needs traversal.

O(n)

❌ High memory usage

Extra pointers in every node.

❌ Poor cache performance

Nodes scattered in memory.

CPU cache inefficient.

Why LinkedList is Rarely Used in Real Systems

Theoretical:

Insertion = O(1)

BUT practical reality:

Finding node itself costs:

O(n)

Modern CPUs favor arrays heavily.

Thus ArrayList often beats LinkedList even in insertions.

Full Complexity Table
Operation	Array	ArrayList	LinkedList
Access	O(1)	O(1)	O(n)
Search	O(n)	O(n)	O(n)
Insert End	O(1)*	O(1) amortized	O(1)
Insert Middle	O(n)	O(n)	O(1)**
Delete Middle	O(n)	O(n)	O(1)**
Memory	Low	Medium	High

* if space available
** if node reference already known

Real Interview Insight
Why ArrayList beats LinkedList practically

Because of:

CPU Cache Locality

Array memory:

1000 1004 1008 1012

CPU fetches nearby memory together.

Very fast.

LinkedList memory:

1000 -> 7000 -> 3000 -> 9000

Memory scattered.

Lots of cache misses.

Huge slowdown.

Important Segregation
